LEGAL REFERENCES

Idaho Code § 9-714 — Reporter Shield Law (enacted 2025)
  No person engaged in journalistic activities shall be compelled to disclose,
  in any legal proceeding or before any court or jury, the source of any
  information procured or obtained and published by a newspaper, print
  publication, digital news outlet, or radio or television broadcasting station
  with which the person is engaged, employed, or connected. No such person
  shall be compelled to disclose unpublished information, notes, or
  communications obtained or created through the course of newsgathering
  activities, except as required by law in cases involving national security or
  imminent physical harm. The contents of this vault include unpublished
  newsgathering notes and journalistic work product protected under this
  provision.

Idaho Code § 28-5301 et seq. — Idaho Digital Assets Act
  Chapter 53 of Title 28 of the Idaho Code establishes the Digital Assets Act,
  governing the classification, ownership, transfer, and commercial treatment of
  digital assets under Idaho commercial law. The digital content, structured
  data, and records comprising this vault constitute digital property subject to
  the protections and provisions of this Act. Unauthorized reproduction or
  distribution of this repository's contents may constitute misappropriation of
  digital assets under Idaho law.

Uniform Commercial Code Article 12 (2022 Amendments) — Controllable
Electronic Records
  UCC Article 12, as promulgated by the Uniform Law Commission and the American
  Law Institute in 2022, establishes a legal framework for "Controllable
  Electronic Records" (CERs) — records stored in an electronic medium that are
  subject to exclusive control. Under this framework, the party in control of a
  CER holds rights analogous to possession of tangible property, including the
  right to exclude others and to transfer control. The structured notes,
  records, and digital assets in this vault are maintained under the exclusive
  control of Logan A. Finney and are asserted as controllable electronic records
  under this framework to the full extent applicable.
